SOS 69069 — PROTOCOL DESCRIPTION

SYSTEM CLASS

Non-financial, event-driven, identity-linked communication protocol



1. CORE PRINCIPLE

SOS is not a token in the traditional sense.

It is:

> An on-chain message emission system with immutable identity anchors and public event logs

The blockchain acts as:

> A global, append-only communication layer (“public wall”)



2. SEED (IDENTITY ROOT)

Each address can declare itself as part of a Seed.

Properties:

A Seed is a cryptographic identity anchor

A Seed is immutable once assigned

An address:

can join a Seed

cannot change or overwrite its Seed

No authority can assign members to a Seed

Each address self-declares its Seed

Meaning:

> A Seed represents a persistent identity grouping across multiple addresses



3. MINT (MESSAGE EMISSION LAYER)

Mint is the only function that modifies on-chain state.

Rules:

1 transaction = 1 atomic mint

1 mint = exactly 1 wei

Mint increases receiver balance only

Sender balance is not affected

No self-mint allowed between addresses of the same Seed

Daily limit:

max 86400 mints per address

3.1 Mint Interpretation

Mint does NOT represent value transfer.

Mint represents:

> A message written to the receiver’s public on-chain wall

Effects:

balanceOf[address] increases

This value represents:

> total number of interactions/messages received

3.2 Public Wall Communication Model

All Mint events are publicly visible on-chain.

However:

> Only the intended receiver can reliably identify which messages are relevant to them

This is achieved through:

address-level filtering

private key-based interpretation

optional off-chain logic

3.3 Message Linking via Mint

Each Mint can be used as a reference anchor for off-chain communication.

Meaning:

> Any Mint you create can be linked to a message in an external application

Example usage:

A user sends a Mint to another address

Off-chain, a message is created referencing that Mint

The receiver detects:

the Mint event

the associated off-chain message

Key Property:

> Messages are publicly broadcast, but meaning is privately resolved



4. TRUST SYSTEM (INTERNAL SIGNAL)

Trust is an event-based message type.

Properties:

Created by any address with a Seed

Can define up to 3 participants:

p1, p2, p3

Roles are free-format identifiers

Includes:

context reference (hash or external link)

optional parentTrust (for history)

Trust Function:

Only assigned participants can emit a Trust signal.

Rules:

Each participant can act only once per Trust

No on-chain storage of agreement data

Only events are emitted

Meaning:

> Trust = message(type = trust)

No enforced semantics beyond signaling.



5. JOIN SYSTEM (EXTERNAL SIGNAL)

Join is an event-based message type.

Properties:

Unlimited participants

Can reference:

a Trust

a parent Join (history chain)

Join Function:

Any address with a Seed can emit a Join.

Rules:

One Join per Seed per event

Trust participants cannot use Join for the same context

Meaning:

> Join = message(type = acknowledgment)



6. EVENT-ONLY ARCHITECTURE

The system does NOT store:

Trust data

Join data

Relationships

Agreement states

Only emits events.

Result:

> Blockchain = immutable message log

NOT a state machine of agreements



7. RANK (OFF-CHAIN METRIC)

Rank is not stored on-chain.

It is computed from events:

Formula:

Rank(seed) =

total Mint received by Seed
minus

total Mint sent by Seed

Purpose:

identity evaluation

interaction density

social signal



8. HARD PROTOCOL CONSTRAINTS

Enforced directly in code:

No ETH accepted

No transfers exist

No allowance system

No burn function

No selfdestruct

No DeFi interaction

No escrow logic

No value storage beyond message counters

No self-mint between same Seed

Critical Guarantee:

> The only state-changing function is Mint

All other functions:

emit events only

do not carry financial meaning



9. SYSTEM NATURE

SOS behaves as:

a communication protocol

an identity-linked event system

an interaction graph builder

It does NOT behave as:

a financial instrument

a payment system

a store of value

an exchange medium



10. FINAL INTERPRETATION

SOS is:

> A public, append-only, identity-aware signaling layer

where interactions are recorded on-chain
and meaning is resolved off-chain

STRONGEST PROPERTY

> Public visibility + private interpretation

All data is open
Only intended participants can interpret relevance



SUMMARY

Mint = message emission

Trust = structured signal (internal)

Join = acknowledgment signal (external)

Seed = immutable identity anchor

Balance = message count

Rank = derived metric

FINAL STATEMENT

SOS is:

> A neutral, non-financial protocol for recording and linking human or system interactions through immutable on-chain events.
